Here's an example code to send a POST request with format data in the body and content-type as multipart/form-data using the requests library in Python:

```python
import requests

url = 'http://example.com/upload'
headers = {
    'Content-Type': 'multipart/form-data; boundary=----WebKitFormBoundary7MA4YWxkTrZu0gW'
}
data = {
    'param1': 'value1',
    'param2': 'value2',
    # Add more parameters if needed
}
files = {
    'file': ('filename.jpg', open('/path/to/filename.jpg', 'rb'), 'image/jpeg')
    # Add more files if needed
}

response = requests.post(url, headers=headers, data=data, files=files)
print(response.text)
```

In the above code, we have defined the URL to which the POST request will be sent and the headers containing the Content-Type header with boundary specified. The data dictionary contains key-value pairs of the form data that needs to be sent in the body. The files dictionary contains the file(s) to be uploaded along with their names and content types. Finally, we use the requests.post() method to send the POST request and print the response text.

You can use MyBatis to delete multiple tables in a single script by creating a custom mapper interface and XML mapper file.

Here's an example of how to do it:

1. Create a custom mapper interface with a method to delete multiple tables:

```java
public interface TableMapper {

    @Delete({ 
        "DROP TABLE IF EXISTS table1;",
        "DROP TABLE IF EXISTS table2;",
        "DROP TABLE IF EXISTS table3;"
    })
    void deleteTables();
}
```

2. Create an XML mapper file with the SQL statements to delete the tables:

```xml
<mapper namespace="com.example.TableMapper">

  <delete id="deleteTables">
     DROP TABLE IF EXISTS table1;
     DROP TABLE IF EXISTS table2;
     DROP TABLE IF EXISTS table3;
  </delete>

</mapper>
```

3. Configure MyBatis to use the custom mapper interface and XML mapper file:

```xml
<!-- MyBatis configuration file -->
<configuration>

    <mappers>
        <mapper resource="com/example/TableMapper.xml"/>
    </mappers>

</configuration>
```

4. Use the mapper interface to delete the tables:

```java
SqlSession sqlSession = sqlSessionFactory.openSession();
TableMapper tableMapper = sqlSession.getMapper(TableMapper.class);
tableMapper.deleteTables();
sqlSession.commit();
sqlSession.close();
```

This will execute the SQL statements in the deleteTables() method of the TableMapper interface and delete the specified tables. Note that you can modify the SQL statements to fit your specific use case. Also, make sure to properly configure your MyBatis environment and connect to your database before executing the script.

If you want to use the DELETE statement to delete data from multiple tables instead of dropping the tables entirely, you can modify the mapper interface and XML mapper file accordingly.

Here's an example of how to delete data from multiple tables using the DELETE statement in MyBatis:

1. Create a custom mapper interface with a method to delete data from multiple tables:

```java
public interface TableMapper {

    @Delete({ 
        "DELETE FROM table1;",
        "DELETE FROM table2;",
        "DELETE FROM table3;"
    })
    void deleteData();
}
```

2. Create an XML mapper file with the SQL statements to delete data from the tables:

```xml
<mapper namespace="com.example.TableMapper">

  <delete id="deleteData">
     DELETE FROM table1;
     DELETE FROM table2;
     DELETE FROM table3;
  </delete>

</mapper>
```

3. Configure MyBatis to use the custom mapper interface and XML mapper file:

```xml
<!-- MyBatis configuration file -->
<configuration>

    <mappers>
        <mapper resource="com/example/TableMapper.xml"/>
    </mappers>

</configuration>
```

4. Use the mapper interface to delete the data from the tables:

```java
SqlSession sqlSession = sqlSessionFactory.openSession();
TableMapper tableMapper = sqlSession.getMapper(TableMapper.class);
tableMapper.deleteData();
sqlSession.commit();
sqlSession.close();
```

This will execute the SQL statements in the `deleteData()` method of the `TableMapper` interface and delete the data from the specified tables. Note that you can modify the SQL statements to fit your specific use case. Also, make sure to properly configure your MyBatis environment and connect to your database before executing the script.

The Apache Commons CLI library allows you to easily support multiple arguments in your command line interface. Here's an example of how to do it:

1. Create an Options object to define your command line options:

```java
Options options = new Options();
options.addOption(Option.builder("a").longOpt("arg1").hasArg().desc("Argument 1").build());
options.addOption(Option.builder("b").longOpt("arg2").hasArg().desc("Argument 2").build());
options.addOption(Option.builder("c").longOpt("arg3").hasArg().desc("Argument 3").build());
```

In this example, we create three options - "arg1", "arg2", and "arg3". The `hasArg()` method specifies that each option accepts an argument.

2. Parse the command line arguments using a `CommandLineParser`:

```java
CommandLineParser parser = new DefaultParser();
try {
    CommandLine cmd = parser.parse(options, args);

    // Access the argument values
    String arg1Value = cmd.getOptionValue("a");
    String arg2Value = cmd.getOptionValue("b");
    String arg3Value = cmd.getOptionValue("c");

    // Do something with the arguments
    // ...
} catch (ParseException e) {
    System.err.println(e.getMessage());
    HelpFormatter formatter = new HelpFormatter();
    formatter.printHelp("MyProgram", options);
}
```

This code uses the `DefaultParser` to parse the command line arguments. The `getOptionValue()` method can be used to retrieve the value of each option. If an option is specified multiple times, only the last value will be used. If an option is not specified, the `getOptionValue()` method will return `null`.

3. Run your program with command line arguments:

```
java MyProgram -a arg1value -b arg2value -c arg3value
```

This will run your program with three command line arguments - "arg1value", "arg2value", and "arg3value".

By defining multiple options, you can create a command line interface that accepts multiple arguments. You can also use different types of options, such as boolean options (`Option.builder("v").longOpt("verbose").desc("Verbose mode").build()`) to enable/disable certain behavior, or options with multiple arguments (`Option.builder("f").longOpt("file").hasArgs().desc("Input files").build()`) to accept multiple input files.
